<?xml version="1.0"?><collection name="D0808-B"><document name="NYT_ENG_20050708.0124"><line>With between 30,000 and 45,000 Assyrians thought to be living in Merced, Stanislaus and San Joaquin counties, the region claims one of the largest such populations in the United States.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050204.1223"><line>A slate of Chaldean and Assyrian Christians called the National Rafidain List polled about 29 percent in the United States, where it found its largest bloc of votes among the 14 nations where elections were held for Iraqis living abroad.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="43"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051120.0580"><line>The four women died instantly, he said.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050407.0103"><line>&quot;We lost a man who was a symbol for peace, justice and faith in the world, and we wish that God will replace him with a man like him,&quot; Hakim said of the pope.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050214.0112"><line>&quot;It's a good beginning.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050407.0103"><line>John Paul opposed the U.S. invasion of Iraq in 2003 and criticized the U.S.-inspired U.N. sanctions imposed after Iraq invaded Kuwait in 1990.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="12,42"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050519.0483"><line>The government should be Islamic but the Koran cannot be the sole source for the constitution,&quot; Delly told a press conference in Paris.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050708.0124"><line>Beyond that, the long-distance lobbying over Iraq's constitution highlights the controversial power the United States retains over a sovereign nation.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050519.0483"><line>The patriarch of the Iraq-based Chaldean Church, Emmanuel Delly, said Thursday that Iraq's future constitution should not solely be based on the Koran, despite the country's overwhelming Muslim majority.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="4" sums="10,11,40,57"><scu uid="7" label="Christians want minority rights enshrined in the constitution" weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050204.1223"><line>Raaed Al-Haddad, 30, of Raleigh, North Carolina, said he voted for the United Iraqi Alliance because he felt it was an inclusive ticket, with Sunni Muslims and Kurds included among its leaders.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="43"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050206.0233"><line>&quot;There were irregularities and we felt that the injustice was inflicted on us,&quot; he said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050214.0112"><line>In addition to the single seat won by the National Rafidain List, which represented Chaldean, Assyrian and other Christian groups, four Christians won seats on the Kurdish ticket and one was elected on the slate of interim Prime Minister Ayad Alawi, Kassab said.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050519.0483"><line>Delly, who has been in France for the past week, met with French President Jacques Chirac on Monday.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051223.0058"><line>Guard Dawood's family is Chaldean but has been attending the church since he was a little boy.</line><line>Worshippers plan to hold mass in the unfinished shell on Sunday.</line><line>She said rehearsals were cancelled last year in the wake of the bombing but this year they went ahead with them.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050407.0103"><line>Under a golden, late afternoon sun, the worshippers passed through a protective cordon of red-bereted soldiers from the newly trained, mostly Muslim Iraqi army.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050206.0233"><line>The demonstrators gathered outside the Green Zone, which houses the offices of the interim Iraqi government as well as the U.S. and British embassies.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050519.0483"><line>With 600,000 followers, the Chaldean Church accounts for the vast majority of Iraq's Christians.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="4" sums="13,40,43,49"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051223.0058"><line>Amid Christmas trees and tales of the jolly, bearded Baba Noel (Santa Claus), many in Iraq's Christian minority dream of leaving the country but bravely continue with the traditions of their faith.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="3" sums="14,36,44"><scu uid="12" label="Iraqi Christians celebrate Christmas" weight="3"/><scu uid="18" label="Some Christians hope to flee Iraq" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050407.0103"><line>Iraqi soldiers in pickup trucks were stationed several blocks from the church in all directions, searching cars, asking for ID cards and politely asking anyone not going to the service to take an alternative route.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050708.0124"><line>The United States, Brown added, will have &quot;some influence&quot; in this, but won't be able to dictate the complete work.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051120.0580"><line>The attack occurred in Baghdad's eastern neighborhood of Ghadeer and valuables were stolen from the house, said police Lt. Ali Mutaab.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051223.0058"><line>There are five major denominations - the largest the Chaldean Catholics - and several smaller ones.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050708.0124"><line>The draft also states that &quot;the Iraqi citizen has the right to freedom of thought, conscience, religious creed and religious rites.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050204.1223"><line>The ticket led expatriate voting around the world and in Iraq in early results from Sunday's vote.</line><line>Each faction is given seats based on its overall share of the vote.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050318.0105"><line>Yacoub, a member of the Chaldean-Assyrian Church, helped recruit Christians to Kirkuk's police force.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050214.0112"><line>But Kassab complained that many Christians in Iraq, particularly in the northern Sunni Muslim province of Nineveh, were unable to cast votes.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051120.0580"><line>Since then thousands of Christians fled to Syria and Jordan.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050407.0103"><line>&quot;I did not care if it is dangerous to come here today,&quot; said a government employee who gave only her first name, Haifa.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051223.0058"><line>A mechanic by training, Dawood, 21, became a guard for his church after it was gutted in a bombing a year ago.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050214.0112"><line>But the country's Christian minority, which makes up about 5 percent of Iraq's 26 million people, secured enough votes for just one Assembly seat.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="7" sums="10,19,22,29,36,48,55"><scu uid="1" label="Christian parties win only one seat in 275-seat National Assembly for Christian Parties" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050204.1223"><line>About a third of expatriate Iraqis who voted by absentee ballot last week in the United States chose the Shiite party backed by Iraq's leading clerics, followed closely by a party made up of Iraqi Christians, according to provisional results released Friday.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="49,5"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051223.0058"><line>&quot;It will be happy even though we live in bad circumstances,&quot; she said walking home with her mother from choir practice.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050708.0124"><line>In June 2003, Cardoza introduced a House resolution expressing concern about the status of Assyrians in post-war Iraq.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="32,5"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051223.0058"><line>Larry Kaplow can be contacted at lkaplowcoxnews.com<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="21"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050407.0103"><line>Iraq has an estimated 800,000 Christians, but another 300,000 had emigrated since 1991, said Yonadam Kanna, one of six Christians elected to Iraq's new National Assembly.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="4" sums="12,21,22,42"><scu uid="3" label="Christians won only six seats in the new National Assembly" weight="1"/><scu uid="11" label="Emigration of Iraqi Christians continues with the number since the American takeover estimated from 20,000 to 200,000" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050206.0233"><line>The Independent Electoral Commission of Iraq is also based inside the compound.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050708.0124"><line>&quot;A number of our young men and women have died to bring them their freedoms,&quot; Cardoza said.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050318.0105"><line>The group also claimed a December 21, 2004 attack on a US base in the northern Iraqi city of Mosul that killed 22 people, including 14 US soldiers.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050708.0124"><line>An engineer now living in Modesto, Kanno did agree with Cardoza that &quot;we want freedom of religion&quot; and &quot;some kind of safe haven&quot; under the new constitution.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050214.0112"><line>&quot;We lost more than 150,000 votes in northern Iraq,&quot; he said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050206.0233"><line>Mosul has become a flashpoint for insurgents battling U.S. and Iraqi security forces in recent weeks.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050407.0103"><line>&quot;Christians need a protector, or father, someone who protects them, and I think the pope is one who protected them.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050214.0112"><line>&quot;We should work toward unity, whether Shia or Sunni or Kurdish.&quot;</line><line>&quot;We need them to reconfirm the rights of all Iraq's minorities and religions,&quot; Kassab said.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="18"/></line><line>It's still flammable,&quot; al-Husainy said.</line><line>Members of the Iraqi Christian minority living in the United States voiced hopes that a spirit of cooperation and national unity would prevail in Iraq even as Shiite Muslims prevailed in that country's first free elections in over 50 years.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="6" sums="13,16,20,23,29,43"/></line><line>Unlike most of Iraq's Sunni Muslim community _ the disenfranchised group believed to be driving the deadly insurgency in the country _ Chaldeans and Assyrians joined Shiites and Kurds in making their voices heard during the elections.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="3" sums="19,37,6"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051223.0058"><line>There is a priest here and our God protects us,&quot; Dawood said last week by the palm tree trunks that form a barrier to the church entrance.</line><line>&quot;All the churches are threatened but we will go to mass.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050708.0124"><line>The resolution gained 10 co-sponsors, including Mariposa Republican George Radanovich, but did not reach the House floor.</line><line>Recently, Cardoza met with His Beatitude Mar Emmanuel III Delly, the patriarch of the Chaldean Catholic Church.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="3,57"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050316.0699"><line>General Waed Yussuf Yacoub, who worked at the interior ministry and was a pillar of the Christian community in Kirkuk, was gunned down when a car pulled up alongside his vehicle, said a police spokesman.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="33"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050519.0483"><line>&quot;Ninety-five percent of the Iraqi people are Muslims.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051223.0058"><line>He lives around the block from St. George's and notes that seven families on his half-mile long street have left the country since early 2003.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050407.0103"><line>Most Christians appeared happy with the extensive security.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050214.0112"><line>Iraqi Americans cast 8,975 votes Jan. 28-30 at a polling site in the Detroit suburb of Southgate.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050708.0124"><line>A current draft of the proposed constitution, translated by George Washington University scholar Nathan Brown, includes a provision stating that &quot;discrimination on the basis of gender, nationality, religion, origin or social standing is forbidden.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051223.0058"><line>That and other church attacks in 2004 killed 20 or so, according to reports at the time.</line><line>So one of the Christmas rituals these days is to make phone calls to close relatives far away.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050708.0124"><line>&quot;All of a sudden, he's pandering to the Assyrian community now that he's got an Assyrian running against him.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050318.0105"><line>It has released video footage showing some of the killings.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050407.0103"><line>&quot;And did you notice that there was no American army around?</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050214.0112"><line>&quot;The Shia are good friends to the Christians,&quot; said Kassab, voicing hopes that the suffering both groups endured under Saddam Hussein's regime would bridge any rifts.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="43"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051223.0058"><line>They held mass in the church the day after the bombing that, despite the extensive damage, did not wound any one in the early morning hours.</line><line>&quot;It is a little bit better because more people are used to the situation,&quot; said Amir Oraha, a spokesman for the largest Christian political party, the Assyrian Democratic Movement.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050708.0124"><line>Iraqi officials insist no extension will be needed.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050206.0233"><line>Hundreds of Iraqis shouted slogans and waived Iraqi flags Sunday outside Baghdad's heavily guarded Green Zone to protest alleged voting irregularities in Mosul that they say prevented tens of thousands from voting in last weekend's landmark elections.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051223.0058"><line>But more Iraqi Christians live outside Iraq than inside, the result of nearly a century of steady emigration.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="37,6"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050519.0483"><line>Iraq's parliament has just set up a committee to draft the constitution by a deadline of August 15.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051223.0058"><line>Desire to emigrate is almost a given.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050708.0124"><line>The transitional law currently governing Iraq calls for a draft of the new constitution to be completed by Aug. 15.</line><line>The local worries and the political response they generate illustrate how ethnic constituencies shape congressional action.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050407.0103"><line>&quot;Officially, the regime said it couldn't protect him,&quot; Sleiman said, adding that he thought Saddam Hussein had been &quot;afraid the pope would have more crowds than him.&quot;<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="21"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050708.0124"><line>&quot;The Assyrian people suffered greatly in their attempts to obtain greater freedom and recognition,&quot; wrote Cardoza, a member of the House International Relations Committee.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051223.0058"><line>Christians have more opportunity for flight than do their Muslim neighbors, who face as many dangers.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050708.0124"><line>Their worries mobilize local lawmakers, who are now starting to lean on the Bush administration.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050214.0112"><line>Turn-out was low in Sunni areas, partly due to security fears and because of Sunni clerics who called for a boycott of the elections.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051223.0058"><line>Like a lot of Iraqi Christians, Wasseem Dawood has adjusted to the new ways of marking Christmas.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050519.0483"><line>Jaafari pledged Sunday to get more Sunnis involved in drafting the constitution after meeting with US Secretary of State Condoleezza Rice during her surprise visit to Iraq.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050407.0103"><line>Inside, amid air smoky with incense, a tearful congregation recalled the Polish-born man who had given help and hope to Iraq's dwindling Christian communities.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="55"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050708.0124"><line>Much closer to home, it could shape at least one local congressional race.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051223.0058"><line>His Greek Catholic(cq) Church of St. George had its walls blown out and its insides charred and gutted.</line><line>The blast blew limbs off the Jesus figure on the crucifix behind the altar but it was preserved, and the stately, domed church is being rebuilt, largely by volunteers.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="5"/></line><line>Dozens of churches are spread through Baghdad, some graceful and domed and some boxy and non-descript.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050204.1223"><line>&quot;We need the Sunnis, the Christians and the Kurds.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050318.0105"><line>The authenticity of the statement could not be confirmed.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050407.0103"><line>John Paul's death &quot;was a loss not only for Iraqi Catholics and Christians but indeed it was a loss for the whole world,&quot; the patriarch said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050204.1223"><line>The American sites included Washington, Chicago, Detroit, Los Angeles and Nashville, Tenn.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050407.0103"><line>&quot;It is a big honor to come here and join our friends and brothers at this service,&quot; said the Iranian, Ali Akbar Hakim.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050204.1223"><line>&quot;We need to make sure we have a good secular government so the constitution of Iraq recognizes the rights of minorities and other ethnic groups,&quot; he said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051223.0058"><line>A philosophy and religion student, she said she would like to go to any country with, &quot;peace and stability.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050318.0105"><line>The Al-Qaeda linked Army of Ansar al-Sunna claimed it had killed a Christian general in the Iraqi police force earlier this week in northern Iraq, in a statement posted on an Islamist website on Friday.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="7" sums="12,23,25,29,42,51,55"><scu uid="8" label="a Christian general in the Iraqi police force was shot dead" weight="4"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051223.0058"><line>Midnight Mass on Christmas Eve is now routinely held in the daylight hours of the afternoon.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050204.1223"><line>The Kurdish ticket Kurdish Alliance List received nearly 17 percent of the U.S. vote, while the list led by current Prime Minister Ayad Allawi, which had been expected to do well among expatriates, only won about 4 percent of votes in the United States.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050519.0483"><line>Delly said he had discussed Iraq's future constitution with the most influential Shiite cleric in the country, Grand Ayatollah Ali Sistani.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050214.0112"><line>A Shiite Muslim clergy-backed slate won 48 percent of the votes and 140 of the 275 National Assembly seats, according to results released Sunday in Baghdad.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050318.0105"><line>&quot;The general was killed and the knights returned safely to base,&quot; it said.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050519.0483"><line>The constitution must &quot;offer religious freedom to all in Iraq, but also personal liberties,&quot; Delly said.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="3" sums="16,37,6"><scu uid="7" label="Christians want minority rights enshrined in the constitution" weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050214.0112"><line>Election officials also said that many polling stations in the province either didn't open or ran out of ballots.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051223.0058"><line>Anita Dawood, Wasseem's 22-year-old sister, has been brushing up on her Christmas carols with the church choir.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050407.0103"><line>&quot;We wish that God will take him to heaven and give his family and friends the patience to withstand this loss.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051223.0058"><line>Some today feel threatened by the Islamic fundamentalism unleashed with the collapse in the old police state.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050407.0103"><line>Delly concelebrated the Arabic-language Mass with the heads of three other Catholic communities here -- Latin, Armenian and Syrian -- and a representative of the papal nuncio's office.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051223.0058"><line>It's been motivated by mob violence going back to the Ottoman Empire's rule of Iraq and spans through the crushing poverty of economic sanctions and Saddam's brutality in the last decade.</line><line>In recent days, children were in the church annex sharpening up their high-pitched, Arabic Jingle Bells and rehearsing the localized journey of the Three Wise Men, tracking the nativity star from the Iraqi cities of Basra, Kirkuk and Suleymaniya.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="21"><scu uid="12" label="Iraqi Christians celebrate Christmas" weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050214.0112"><line>Not perfect, but a good beginning,&quot; said Husham al-Husainy of the Karbalaa Islamic Education Center in Dearborn.</line><line>For a fragile democracy to take root after 35 years of Saddam's dictatorship and two years of occupation, Iraqis, the U.S. government and Iraq's neighbors must defend it against those who prefer chaos or oppression, he said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051223.0058"><line>Most already have relatives abroad and enough money to move, but some say it is harder to leave now than under Saddam, when Christian countries were looser with asylum requests.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050206.0233"><line>In November, rebels launched an uprising there that forced nearly the entire police force to desert their posts.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050407.0103"><line>When you have a soul of faith, it kills every fear inside your body.&quot;</line><line>Sleiman said his Roman Catholic community had 60,000 members before the 1991 Persian Gulf War; now it has around 5,000.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051120.0580"><line>Christians, mostly from the early Assyrian and Chaldean churches, were targeted in August 2004 when four churches in Baghdad and one in Mosul were blown up in a coordinated series of car bombings.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050407.0103"><line>Sleiman and Delly both recalled the pope's disappointment at not being able to visit Iraq in 1999.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050318.0105"><line>The general, who worked at the interior ministry and was a pillar of the Christian community in Kirkuk, was gunned down when a car pulled up alongside his vehicle, they said.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="33"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050407.0103"><line>It is a full Iraqi operation.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050708.0124"><line>Still, Cardoza said that &quot;we have a certain amount of pressure we can bring to bear&quot; on the Iraqis who are writing their nation's new governing documents.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051223.0058"><line>At St. George's, as in many churches, there is an informal approach to the denominational lines and Christians of different sects attend.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050708.0124"><line>One six-month extension is permitted, in case Iraqi officials cannot meet the original deadlines.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051120.0580"><line>Ghadeer is a predominantly Christian neighborhood and is known to be calm compared to other Baghdad neighborhoods.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="25,47"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051223.0058"><line>On Oct. 16, 2004, bombers struck five churches, including St. George's, nearly simultaneously.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050204.1223"><line>On the Net:</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050407.0103"><line>&quot;If I die, I will die here in the church with Jesus.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050214.0112"><line>On the Net:</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051223.0058"><line>Estimates vary but there are perhaps 800,000 Christians in Iraq making up about 3 percent of the population.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050214.0112"><line>Chaldean Americans, who are heavily concentrated in the Detroit area, were pleased to see their homeland moving in a democratic direction after decades of dictatorial rule, Kassab said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050708.0124"><line>Some Republicans, though, view Cardoza's solicitude skeptically.</line><line>At the same time, with Muslims making up more than 90 percent of Iraq's population, Islam may well be declared the nation's official religion.</line><line>&quot;The reports they are hearing is that (Iraq is) drafting a fundamentalist Islamic document.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050206.0233"><line>The demonstrators were mainly Iraqi Christians, Turkomen and Yazidis _ members of a small religion in the north _ who say polling centers never opened in their neighborhoods in the turbulent northern city and in the surrounding Ninevah province.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050204.1223"><line>Some voters had to drive hundreds of miles twice, once to register and a second time to vote.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="48"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050214.0112"><line>A Kurdish ticket got 26 percent and 75 seats.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050407.0103"><line>&quot;The pope won the hearts of everybody because he worked for the good of all,&quot; said Patriarch Emmanuel Delly, the head of Iraq's Chaldean Catholic Church.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050318.0105"><line>Iraq's 700,000 Christian community has been targeted by rebels since the fall of Saddam Hussein's regime in April 2003 and many members of the dwindling minority have fled the country.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050204.1223"><line>The party also polled well in Australia, where 36 percent voted for it.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050206.0233"><line>Some of those that did open could not be supplied with ballots and other election materials, officials have said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051223.0058"><line>&quot;People should live their lives.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050206.0233"><line>A spokesman for Chaldean and Assyrian parties, William Warda, said the irregularities prevented 200,000 people from voting.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050204.1223"><line>Al-Haddad, a Shiite Muslim, was also pleased that some of the minority groups had a strong showing in the U.S. voting.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050214.0112"><line>&quot;We are extending our hands to our brother Shiites, and Sunnis in Iraq, to work together to have a... better, democratic Iraq,&quot; said Joseph Kassab, president of the U.S. branch of the Chaldean National Congress.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050519.0483"><line>Iraq's small Christian community represents only about three percent of the country's population.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="5" sums="13,40,41,43,49"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050206.0233"><line>&quot;We are protesting because we have been deprived of our right to participate in the elections,&quot; said Shameil Benjamin from a Christian party called the Democratic Assyrian Movement.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="41"><scu uid="5" label="many prevented many from voting" weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050214.0112"><line>The imam at the area's leading Iraqi Shiite mosque said he, too, felt hope mixed with fear.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051223.0058"><line>&quot;If I have the ability, I will go,&quot; he said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050214.0112"><line>But with the National Rafidain List securing just 36,255 votes compared to the more than 4 million votes for the Shiite's United Iraqi Alliance, Christians must pin their sights on partnership and support from the other groups to ensure that their interests are secured as the Assembly drafts Iraq's new constitution.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051223.0058"><line>&quot;(But) yeah, anyone who holds a Kalashnikov is in danger.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050316.0699"><line>A Christian general in the Iraqi police force was shot dead late Wednesday as he drove home in the northern oil city of Kirkuk, police said.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="11" sums="11,14,19,23,25,33,41,44,48,49,51"><scu uid="8" label="a Christian general in the Iraqi police force was shot dead" weight="4"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050708.0124"><line>Kanno's parents left their native Iraq in 1957-58; he was subsequently born in England, and has lived in the United States since 1981.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051120.0580"><line>Gunmen stormed a house in eastern Baghdad Sunday night and shot dead four Christian women in an apparent robbery, police said.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="25,51"><scu uid="9" label="In November in Baghdad gunmen killed four Christian women" weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050407.0103"><line>In a display of solidarity, five Shiites, including a black-turbaned cleric from Iran, attended the Mass for the pope at St. Joseph's.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="19"><scu uid="10" label="Catholics celebrated a mass for Pope John Paul II" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050708.0124"><line>Dominated by Shiites, the committee includes one Assyrian Christian, 15 Kurds and one communist, among others.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="32,35"><scu uid="16" label="The 71-member committee drafting the constitution included only one Christian" weight="1"/></annotation></line><line>It is supposed to be submitted to the Iraqi public for ratification by Oct. 15.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050204.1223"><line>The United Iraqi Alliance, which was endorsed by the influential Shiite cleric Grand Ayatollah Ali Al-Sistani, won nearly 32 percent of the 24,278 valid votes cast at five polling sites in the United States.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050407.0103"><line>&quot;John Paul II has been very close to Iraqis,&quot; Archbishop Jean Sleiman of Baghdad's Roman Catholic, or Latin, community said in an interview earlier this week.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050519.0483"><line>The draft is then to be put to a nationwide referendum by October 15 under a deadline set by the US-inspired transitional administrative law (TAL) currently governing Iraq.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050708.0124"><line>Assyrian media serves the region, as do Assyrian churches, and politicians know to be attentive.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050519.0483"><line>He was to celebrate a mass with the Archbishop of Paris, Andre Vingt-Trois, on Sunday before leaving the country.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050708.0124"><line>Local Assyrians worry the new constitution will favor Islam over Christianity.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051223.0058"><line>And this year, he will keep watch outside his church with a Kalashnikov rifle.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050708.0124"><line>&quot;The Assyrians, to be perfectly honest, until now haven't seen too much of Congressman Cardoza,&quot; said John Kanno, an Assyrian who has declared his candidacy against Cardoza.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="57"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050204.1223"><line>Joseph Kassab, president of the Chaldean National Congress, based in the Detroit area, said more Christians compose a large portion of the Iraqis living in the United States, which likely accounted for the strong showing by the National Rafidain List.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="33"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050214.0112"><line>&quot;There is so much potential of civil war, of ethnic clashing.</line><line>In all, 24,335 of the 265,148 overseas votes were cast in the United States.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051223.0058"><line>Along with the reconstruction of the church itself they have added a 12-foot-high wall around the perimeter.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050206.0233"><line>Banners held aloft read, &quot;Assyrians, Turkomens, Yazidis have the right to enjoy the essence of freedom&quot; and &quot;We demand our democratic rights and we reject marginalization.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051223.0058"><line>Northern Iraq has large Christian communities.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="4" sums="13,32,37,6"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050708.0124"><line>In an interview, Brown said Friday that while the &quot;principles&quot; of religious tolerance will be articulated in the constitution, &quot;the devil will be in the details&quot; as the new Iraqi Parliament begins writing specific laws.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051223.0058"><line>Like always, he will visit relatives, eat rich foods and buy new clothes.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050708.0124"><line>The Assyrian religious leader advised Cardoza about developments in Iraq, prompting the congressman to echo the concerns in a July 6 letter to President Bush.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050206.0233"><line>A team of independent lawyers is investigating those and other complaints in the city and is to report back to the electoral commission.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050708.0124"><line>&quot;(They are) incredibly concerned about the current drafting of the constitution,&quot; Merced Democrat Dennis Cardoza said.</line><line>This week, the Iraqi National Assembly committee drafting the constitution was expanded to 71 members with the addition of 15 Sunnis.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="35"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051223.0058"><line>He got 20 days of training in how to shoot straight and spot terrorists, a police salary of about $125 a month and a rifle from the government agency that supports churches.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050204.1223"><line>Kassab said he feared the expected Shiite majority will not be attentive to minority parties and groups in Iraq, such as Christians.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="8" sums="10,14,22,32,36,37,44,6"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050519.0483"><line>The Chaldean patriarch said Sistani had told him he &quot;did not want a government that was only for Shiites or Muslims in general&quot;, adding that new Prime Minister Ibrahim Jaafari &quot;says the same thing&quot;.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050204.1223"><line>&quot;We need this in the government,&quot; he said.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050318.0105"><line>The Army of Ansar al-Sunna has claimed a string of attacks in Iraq, including murders of foreign hostages and Iraqis accused of &quot;collaborating&quot; with US-led forces.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050407.0103"><line>Many in the congregation said it was a service they could not miss, despite the violence that makes travel risky in the Iraqi capital.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050318.0105"><line>&quot;On the main Baghdad road in the northern city of Kirkuk, a group of fighters... attacked the head of the police, a Christian general, with assault rifles,&quot; said the group in an overnight statement.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050214.0112"><line>Kassab said that the main concern for Iraqi Christians now is that minority rights be enshrined in the constitution to be written by the National Assembly.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="2" sums="13,20"><scu uid="7" label="Christians want minority rights enshrined in the constitution" weight="3"/><scu uid="19" label="Constitution to be written by the National Assembly" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051223.0058"><line>Samir Naum al-Hayak, 43, a tool shop employee, will be getting in touch with brothers and other kin in Detroit, Chicago and Denmark.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050204.1223"><line>Results were released by the International Organization for Migration, which ran the overseas voting.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="5"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050316.0699"><line>Yacoub, a member of the Chaldean-Assyrian Church, helped recruit Christians to Kirkuk's police force.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="3" sums="16,41,57"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051223.0058"><line>Christian activists give differing numbers from 20,000 to 200,000 for the number of Christians who have left the country since the American takeover.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050407.0103"><line>In a city where churches have been bombed by Muslim insurgents and Christians are an imperiled minority, several hundred Catholics gathered at St. Joseph's Chaldean Church on Thursday to attend a special Mass for Pope John Paul II.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="11"><scu uid="10" label="Catholics celebrated a mass for Pope John Paul II" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050708.0124"><line>&quot;We're going to stay on that timetable,&quot; Bush told reporters last month, following a meeting with Iraqi Prime Minister Ibrahim al-Jaafari, &quot;and it's important for the Iraqi people to know we are.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050206.0233"><line>Electoral commission officials in Baghdad have acknowledged that many polling sites never opened or opened late on Jan. 30 and said that was because of security concerns.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050318.0105"><line>Police had said earlier that General Waed Yussuf Yacoub was shot dead late on Wednesday as he drove home in the northern oil city of Kirkuk.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050407.0103"><line>&quot;I feel so safe,&quot; said Abu Adwar as he walked to the church with his wife and two children.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050204.1223"><line>Some Iraqi groups criticized the U.S. vote because it was held at only five sites and organized in just a few weeks.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050316.0699"><line>Iraq's 700,000 Christian community has been targeted by rebels since the fall of Saddam Hussein's regime in April 2003 and many members of the dwindling minority have fled the country.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="6" sums="14,20,22,32,40,44"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050204.1223"><line>The votes will help determine the makeup of a new National Assembly, which will draft Iraq's new constitution.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051223.0058"><line>But this year was not as deadly for Christians and some say this third Christmas in the chaotic aftermath of the U.S.-led invasion will be more relaxed if only because they are now familiar with the dangers.</line><line>&quot;I have to protect the church.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050708.0124"><line>&quot;It would be outrageous for minorities who have suffered and sacrificed so much to not be afforded protection under the new constitution.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051223.0058"><line>For now, she plans to decorate the tree, bake cakes and make the usual nativity scene in their house.</line><line>Rarely do they now hold the parties, primed with whiskey and running into the early morning, that brought large numbers of Christians and their Muslim friends together in social clubs and hotels.</line></document></collection>